[On 11 Jul 2018, the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) published a scientific opinion on African swine fever (ASF) in wild boar [http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/efsajournal/pub/5344]. The opinion, authored by the EFSA AHAW Panel (EFSA Panel on Animal Health and Welfare) was briefly presented in posting 20180711.5899939.

The following comments, received from AHAW (20180714.5903959), are relevant to the situation in Belgium and the related responses:

"1. Preventive measures to reduce and stabilise wild boar density, before ASF introduction, will be beneficial both in reducing the probability of exposure of the population to ASF and the efforts needed for potential emergency actions (i.e., less carcass removal) if an ASF incursion were to occur. Following focal ASF introduction, the wild boar populations should be kept undisturbed for a short period (e.g., hunting ban on all species, leave crops unharvested to provide food and shelter within the affected area), and drastic reduction of the wild boar population may be performed only ahead of the ASF advance front in the free populations. Following the decline in the epidemic, as demonstrated through passive surveillance, active population management should be reconsidered. This will reduce the chances of exposure to susceptible pigs and the efforts of emergency measures (e.g., carcass removal)."

"2. Based on practical and theoretical considerations, it is currently not possible to establish wild boar density thresholds that do not allow sustaining ASF. There are many drivers determining whether ASF can be sustained, including heterogeneous population structures and human‚Äêmediated spread, and there are still unknowns on the importance of different transmission modes in the epidemiology."

EFSA have produced an animation to inform the public about ASF and how it can be prevented: African swine fever -- how to stay one step ahead [https://youtu.be/eyQ4t1wHl2M]. - Mod.AS

